        Breaking Change: A recent change to the code has resulted in several API paths being refactored. Most notable is api/thing/ (which returns a set of Things)
        has been renamed api/things/ (plural). We have also dropped the separate PUT and POST methods for updating a Thing as the distinction created more confusion
        than anything else. Going forward we will only be using POST. We also moved the api/send/{thing id}?{message method to the more sensible api/thing/{thing id}/send/{message}.
    </div>*@

<hr class="featurette-divider">
<a name="Simple" style="position: relative; padding-top: 50px">&#x200B;</a>
<div class="row featurette">
    <div class="col-md-9">
        <h2 class="featurette-heading">Simple<span class="text-muted"> but not simplistic</span></h2>
        <p class="lead">
            Iotiva's architecture is unabashedly lean, using a few primitives as possible.
        </p>

        <p>
            fundamental design principal was that Things should
            self-define themselves through the data they share.
        </p>
        <p>
            To this end, Iotiva uses an extremely lean Thing object that contains only the properties that
            were absolutely required for Iotiva to function. Everything else is stored in a key-value property bag that can be completely unique to each Thing (up to 200 per Thing).
        </p>
    </div>
    <div class="col-md-3 ">
        <img class="img-responsive img-rounded" style="width: 250px; height: 250px;" src="~/Images/Simple.jpg">
    </div>
</div>

<hr class="featurette-divider">
<a name="Scalable" style="position: relative; padding-top: 50px">&#x200B;</a>
<div class="row featurette" id="">
    <div class="col-md-9">
        <h2 class="featurette-heading">Scalable<span class="text-muted"> without a PhD</span></h2>
        <p class="lead">
            Iotiva is powered by Microsoft Azure.
        </p>
        <p>
            Specifically we leverage Azure WebSites, Table Storage and Service Bus. These core services provide multiple inflection points to
            scale the service.
        </p>
        <p>
            Azure allows Iotiva to maintain high-performance while minimizing the costs; we only need to scale the services to mean the particular load rather than
            having to spin up entire VM's. It also allows us to handle large bursts of traffic without falling over as the IO capabilities of Tables and Queues are ridiculously large.
        </p>
    </div>
    <div class="col-md-3">
        <img class="img-responsive img-rounded" style="width: 250px; height: 250px;" src="~/Images/Scalable.jpg" alt="Generic placeholder image">
    </div>
</div>

<hr class="featurette-divider">
<a name="Practical" style="position: relative; padding-top: 50px">&#x200B;</a>
<div class="row featurette" id="pracinfo">
    <div class="col-md-9">
        <h2 class="featurette-heading">Practical<span class="text-muted"> with pizazz</span></h2>
        <p class="lead">
            The inspiration for Iotiva came from an discussion with a fellow hacker over the cost of the cloud.
        </p>
        <p>
            The assumption was that the various cloud services (Azure, AWS, etc) were
            out of reach for the horsiest developer. To test this assumption I deiced to built a small proof of concept to collect data from my various micro-controllers. I placed one constraint on the POC,
            it must cost less than $20 a month. After a few weeks of tinkering I had a completed POC. Not only had I beat the $20/month constraint, it came in under $10!
        </p>
        <p>
            Over the next few months I continued to refine and redactor my little POC into Iotiva. These refinments continue and will be rolled out continually. I will share a formal road map soon but
            the near-term will include private repositories (i.e. non-public Things), eventing (allowing for command-and-control of things) and SDK's for a number of languages and platforms (C#, NETMF, Arduino, JavaScript, Node.js, etc.)
        </p>
    </div>
    <div class="col-md-3">
        <img class="img-responsive img-rounded" style="width: 250px; height: 250px;" src="~/Images/Practical.jpg" alt="Generic placeholder image">
    </div>
</div>